🏛️ Complaint Text Classification and Government Department Recommendation System¶

🧾 Project Overview¶

  • Duration: February 2025 – April 2025
  • Type: Individual Project
  • Description:
    Developed a natural language processing (NLP) system that classifies user-submitted complaint texts into 18 categories.
    The project includes a comparison of Korean BERT-based pretrained models using transfer learning to identify the optimal classifier.
    Additionally, it provides corresponding central government department information, such as official websites and representative contact numbers, based on the predicted category.

🛠 Technologies Used¶

📦 Frameworks & Libraries¶

  • Hugging Face Transformers
  • PyTorch
  • Pandas / NumPy
  • Matplotlib / Seaborn
  • Scikit-learn

💻 Development Environment¶

  • Python
  • Jupyter Notebook
  • Visual Studio Code (VSCode)

🧠 Modeling Techniques¶

  • TF-IDF + LightGBM (Baseline)
  • Pretrained Korean BERT models (KoBERT, KcBERT, KcELECTRA)
  • Fine-tuning with Early Stopping

📂 Dataset Information¶

  • Source: AIHub – AI Language Data for Complaint Handling Automation
  • Format: JSON (split into source data and labeled data)

Components:¶

  • Source Data: id, text
  • Labeled Data: id, category, subcategory, prediction, department, Q_refined, and more

Data Preprocessing:¶

  • Extracted and transformed relevant columns from JSON into CSV:

    • source_data_train.csv, source_data_val.csv
    • labeled_data_train.csv, labeled_data_val.csv

  • Final preprocessed datasets:

    • complaint_combined_train.csv
    • complaint_combined_val.csv

⚠️ This project was implemented using machine learning and deep learning techniques.
Due to variations in initial weights, data shuffling, and execution environments,
the model's performance and visualizations may differ slightly across runs.
As such, the results generated during execution may not exactly match those presented in this documentation.

📄 Data Extraction and Transformation¶

✅ Processing Steps¶

  1. Labeled Data

    • Extracted id and labeling.intent.category fields from each JSON document → saved as CSV

  2. Source Data

    • Extracted id and Q_refined fields from each JSON document → saved as CSV

  3. Used glob + recursive search to automatically collect all nested JSON files

  4. These steps served as a preliminary stage for merging datasets based on id

In [28]:
import os
import glob
import json
import pandas as pd

def parse_documents(f):
    data = json.load(open(f, encoding='utf-8'))
    return data['documents'] if isinstance(data, dict) and 'documents' in data else data

def extract_labeling_data(files):
    return pd.DataFrame([
        {'id': d.get('id', ''), 'category': d.get('labeling', {}).get('intent', {}).get('category', '')}
        for f in files
        for d in parse_documents(f)
    ])

def extract_raw_data(files):
    return pd.DataFrame([
        {'id': d.get('id', ''), 'text': d.get('Q_refined', '')}
        for f in files
        for d in parse_documents(f)
    ])

if __name__ == '__main__':
    base = 'dataset'
    paths = {
        '라벨링데이터_train.csv': glob.glob(f'{base}/1.Training/라벨링데이터/**/*.json', recursive=True),
        '원천데이터_train.csv': glob.glob(f'{base}/1.Training/원천데이터/**/*.json', recursive=True),
        '라벨링데이터_val.csv': glob.glob(f'{base}/2.Validation/라벨링데이터/**/*.json', recursive=True),
        '원천데이터_val.csv': glob.glob(f'{base}/2.Validation/원천데이터/**/*.json', recursive=True),
    }
    for name, files in paths.items():
        df = extract_labeling_data(files) if '라벨링' in name else extract_raw_data(files)
        df.to_csv(name, index=False, encoding='utf-8')

🔍 ID Matching Check Before Merging¶

This step verifies whether the id values in the source and labeled datasets match prior to merging.

✅ Purpose¶

  • To ensure that the source data (id, text) and labeled data (id, category)
    can be correctly merged based on a common id field
  • Visually confirm that all IDs exist in both datasets
In [ ]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from matplotlib_venn import venn2

train_org_ids = set(df_org_train["id"].unique())
train_lb_ids  = set(df_lb_train["id"].unique())
val_org_ids   = set(df_org_val["id"].unique())
val_lb_ids    = set(df_lb_val["id"].unique())

fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(16, 8))

🧹 Duplicate Text Removal and Cleaning¶

✅ Purpose¶

  • To prevent performance degradation and potential bias in the classification model,
    duplicate entries with the same text value were removed from the dataset.

🔍 Criteria for Removing Duplicates¶

  1. Group rows with identical text values
  2. If all rows in the group share the same category, keep them as-is
  3. If multiple categories exist within the group,
    → retain only one representative row based on the most frequent category
In [ ]:
import seaborn as sns

train_counts = df_merged_train.groupby("text").size().reset_index(name="count")
val_counts   = df_merged_val.groupby("text").size().reset_index(name="count")

train_dup_count = (train_counts["count"] >= 2).sum()
val_dup_count   = (val_counts["count"] >= 2).sum()

data = pd.DataFrame({
    "Dataset": ["Train", "Validation"],
    "Duplicate_Text_Count": [train_dup_count, val_dup_count]
})

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
ax = sns.barplot(x="Dataset", y="Duplicate_Text_Count", data=data, palette="viridis")

for patch in ax.patches:
    height = patch.get_height()
    ax.text(
        patch.get_x() + patch.get_width() / 2, 
        height, 
        f'{height:.0f}', 
        ha='center', 
        va='bottom', 
        fontsize=12,
        color='black',
        weight='bold'
    )

plt.title("중복 텍스트 수")
plt.ylabel("중복 텍스트 개수")
plt.xlabel("")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

train_grouped = df_merged_train.groupby("text")["category"].nunique()
train_dup = (train_grouped >= 2).sum()

val_grouped = df_merged_val.groupby("text")["category"].nunique()
val_dup = (val_grouped >= 2).sum()

data = pd.DataFrame({
    "Dataset": ["Train", "Validation"],
    "Duplication_Count": [train_dup, val_dup]
})

plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
ax = sns.barplot(x="Dataset", y="Duplication_Count", data=data, palette="viridis")

for container in ax.containers:

import pandas as pd

def deduplicate_text_with_mode_category(df):
    def get_representative(group):
        mode = group['category'].mode()
        return group[group['category'] == mode.iloc[0]].iloc[0]

    return df.groupby('text', group_keys=False).apply(get_representative)

# 중복 제거
df_merged_train = deduplicate_text_with_mode_category(df_merged_train)
df_merged_train = deduplicate_text_with_mode_category(df_merged_val)

🧮 Train/Validation Split Ratio Check¶

✅ Purpose¶

  • To verify that the ratio between the training and validation sets is appropriate relative to the entire dataset.
In [ ]:
import np

train_count = len(df_merged_train)
val_count = len(df_merged_val)

counts = [train_count, val_count]
labels = ["Train", "Validation"]

def make_autopct(values):
    def my_autopct(pct):
        absolute = int(round(pct/100. * np.sum(values)))
        return "{:.1f}%\n({:d})".format(pct, absolute)
    return my_autopct

plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))
plt.pie(counts, labels=labels, autopct=make_autopct(counts), startangle=90)
plt.title("데이터 분포")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

🔧 Adjusting Train/Validation Split Ratio¶

✅ Problem¶

  • After preprocessing (data cleaning, integrity checks, duplicate removal),
    the dataset became heavily imbalanced: Train 97.3% vs Validation 2.7%

🔁 Adjustment Strategy¶

  • 10% of the training data was reallocated to the validation set
  • To preserve the class distribution, stratified sampling was applied during the split
In [ ]:
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

train_90, train_10 = train_test_split(
    df_train,
    test_size=0.10,
    stratify=df_train['category'],
)

df_merged_val = pd.concat([df_merged_val, train_10], ignore_index=True)

train_90.to_csv('민원통합데이터_train.csv', index=False, encoding='utf-8')
df_merged_val.to_csv('민원통합데이터_val.csv', index=False, encoding='utf-8')

import numpy as np

df_train = pd.read_csv("민원통합데이터_train.csv")
df_val   = pd.read_csv("민원통합데이터_val.csv")

train_count = len(df_train)
val_count = len(df_val)

counts = [train_count, val_count]
labels = ["Train", "Validation"]

def make_autopct(values):
    def my_autopct(pct):
        absolute = int(round(pct/100. * np.sum(values)))
        return "{:.1f}%\n({:d})".format(pct, absolute)
    return my_autopct

plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))
plt.pie(counts, labels=labels, autopct=make_autopct(counts), startangle=90)
plt.title("데이터 분포")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

📊 Category Distribution Check¶

✅ Purpose¶

  • To examine how evenly each category is distributed before training the classification model
  • Severe class imbalance can lead to model bias toward certain categories,
    so this step helps identify such issues in advance
In [ ]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.font_manager as fm

train_counts = df_train["category"].value_counts()
val_counts = df_val["category"].value_counts()

all_categories = sorted(set(train_counts.index) | set(val_counts.index))
color_palette = plt.cm.tab20.colors
color_map = {cat: color_palette[i % len(color_palette)] for i, cat in enumerate(all_categories)}
train_colors = [color_map[cat] for cat in train_counts.index]
val_colors = [color_map[cat] for cat in val_counts.index]

fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(14, 8))

axes[0].barh(train_counts.index, train_counts.values, color=train_colors)
axes[0].set_title("Train Category Count")
axes[0].set_xlabel("건수")

axes[1].barh(val_counts.index, val_counts.values, color=val_colors)
axes[1].set_title("Validation Category Count")
axes[1].set_xlabel("건수")

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

  • Overall, categories such as 'Automobile', 'Safety & Construction', and 'Transportation' are highly represented,
    while categories like 'Information & Communication', 'Land', and 'Agriculture & Livestock' have relatively few samples.

  • Both the training and validation sets maintain a similar distribution pattern,
    indicating that stratified sampling was successfully applied.

  • Given this class imbalance, it is important to consider strategies to mitigate imbalance during model training,
    such as applying class weights or using evaluation metrics like F1-score.

⚡️ Baseline Performance Evaluation using LightGBM¶

✅ Purpose¶

  • To quickly evaluate classification performance using a LightGBM model
    on the preprocessed and deduplicated dataset
  • This serves as a baseline metric for comparison with deep learning models

🔄 Processing Pipeline¶

  1. Convert text (text) into numerical vectors using TF-IDF vectorization
  2. Train a LightGBM classifier
  3. Make predictions and evaluate performance on the validation set
  • LightGBM is a fast and efficient baseline model, useful for understanding the overall trend of the dataset.
In [ ]:
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder
from lightgbm import LGBMClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report, confusion_matrix
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# 데이터 로딩
df_train = pd.read_csv("민원통합데이터_train.csv")
df_val = pd.read_csv("민원통합데이터_val.csv")

# 텍스트와 라벨 추출
X_train = df_train["text"]
y_train = df_train["category"]
X_val = df_val["text"]
y_val = df_val["category"]

# 라벨 인코딩
le = LabelEncoder()
y_train_enc = le.fit_transform(y_train)
y_val_enc = le.transform(y_val)

# TF-IDF 벡터화
vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer(max_features=50000, ngram_range=(1, 2))
X_train_vec = vectorizer.fit_transform(X_train)
X_val_vec = vectorizer.transform(X_val)

# LightGBM 분류기
model = LGBMClassifier(random_state=42, n_estimators=300, learning_rate=0.1, n_jobs=-1, verbose=100)
model.fit(X_train_vec, y_train_enc)

# 예측 및 평가
y_pred = model.predict(X_val_vec)
acc = accuracy_score(y_val_enc, y_pred)
print(f"\n✅ 정확도: {acc:.4f}\n")

# 상세 리포트
print("📊 분류 리포트:")
print(classification_report(y_val_enc, y_pred, target_names=le.classes_))

# 혼동 행렬
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
cm = confusion_matrix(y_val_enc, y_pred)
sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap="Blues", 
            xticklabels=le.classes_, yticklabels=le.classes_)
plt.title("Confusion Matrix")
plt.xlabel("Predicted")
plt.ylabel("Actual")
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.yticks(rotation=0)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

📊 Performance Summary¶

  • Accuracy: 0.6151
  • Macro F1-Score: 0.50
  • Weighted F1-Score: 0.60
  • The model showed moderate overall accuracy,
    and maintained a reasonable level of performance despite class imbalance.

📉 Per-Class Performance Analysis¶

  • High-performing classes:

    • Automobile (F1: 0.82): large number of samples and distinctive text features
    • Other stable categories include Taxation, Water & Sewage, and Environmental Cleaning

  • Low-performing classes:

    • Information & Communication, General, Administration, and Land:
      lower F1-scores due to sparse data or ambiguous expressions

  • Notably, Information & Communication had precision and recall of 0,
    indicating complete failure in classification.

🧭 Confusion Matrix Interpretation¶

  • High confusion observed between several class pairs
    • e.g., Transportation ↔ Automobile, Safety & Construction ↔ Transportation
  • Some classes were frequently misclassified into multiple other categories
    (e.g., General, Building Permit, etc.)

🧠 Classification Performance using SKT KoBERT¶

✅ Model Details¶

  • Model: skt/kobert-base-v1
  • Max Input Length: 256
  • Token Type IDs: All set to 0 (for KoBERT compatibility)
  • Training Method: Hugging Face Trainer with EarlyStopping
In [ ]:
import os
os.environ["CUDA_LAUNCH_BLOCKING"] = "1"

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import torch
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report
from datasets import Dataset
from transformers import (
    AutoTokenizer,
    AutoModelForSequenceClassification,
    Trainer,
    TrainingArguments,
    EarlyStoppingCallback
)

# 1. 데이터 로딩 및 라벨 인코딩 (컬럼명: labels)
def load_and_encode_data(train_path, val_path):
    df_train = pd.read_csv(train_path)
    df_val = pd.read_csv(val_path)

    le = LabelEncoder()
    df_train['labels'] = le.fit_transform(df_train['category'])
    df_val['labels'] = le.transform(df_val['category'])

    return df_train, df_val, le

# 토크나이징 함수
def tokenize_dataset(dataset, tokenizer):
    def tokenize_fn(batch):
        out = tokenizer(batch['text'], padding='max_length', truncation=True, max_length=256)
        if "token_type_ids" in out:
            out["token_type_ids"] = [[0] * len(ids) for ids in out["input_ids"]]
        return out

    return dataset.map(tokenize_fn, batched=True)

# 평가 메트릭 함수
def compute_metrics(eval_pred):
    logits, labels = eval_pred
    preds = np.argmax(logits, axis=-1)
    return {"accuracy": accuracy_score(labels, preds)}

# 메인 실행 함수
def main():
    model_name = "skt/kobert-base-v1"

    # 데이터 로딩 및 라벨 인코딩
    df_train, df_val, le = load_and_encode_data("민원통합데이터_train.csv", "민원통합데이터_val.csv")

    # HuggingFace Dataset 변환
    dataset_train = Dataset.from_pandas(df_train[["text", "labels"]])
    dataset_val = Dataset.from_pandas(df_val[["text", "labels"]])

    # 토크나이저 및 토큰화
    tokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained(model_name, use_fast=False)
    tokenized_train = tokenize_dataset(dataset_train, tokenizer)
    tokenized_val = tokenize_dataset(dataset_val, tokenizer)

    # 모델 로딩
    model = AutoModelForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained(model_name, num_labels=len(le.classes_))

    # 학습 설정
    training_args = TrainingArguments(
        output_dir="./kobert-results",
        evaluation_strategy="epoch",
        save_strategy="epoch",
        learning_rate=2e-5,
        per_device_train_batch_size=64,
        per_device_eval_batch_size=64,
        num_train_epochs=100,
        weight_decay=0.01,
        load_best_model_at_end=True,
        metric_for_best_model="eval_loss",
        greater_is_better=False,
        logging_dir="./kobert-logs",
        fp16=torch.cuda.is_available(),
        dataloader_num_workers=4
    )

    # Trainer 생성
    trainer = Trainer(
        model=model,
        args=training_args,
        train_dataset=tokenized_train,
        eval_dataset=tokenized_val,
        tokenizer=tokenizer,
        compute_metrics=compute_metrics,
        callbacks=[EarlyStoppingCallback(early_stopping_patience=10)]
    )

    # 학습
    trainer.train()

    # 모델 저장
    model.save_pretrained("./kobert_final_model")
    tokenizer.save_pretrained("./kobert_final_model")

    # 예측
    preds_output = trainer.predict(tokenized_val)
    pred_labels = np.argmax(preds_output.predictions, axis=-1)

    # 결과 저장
    result_df = pd.DataFrame({
        "text": df_val["text"],
        "true_label": df_val["category"],
        "pred_label": le.inverse_transform(pred_labels)
    })
    result_df.to_csv("kobert_val_predictions.csv", index=False, encoding="utf-8")

    # 평가 출력
    print(f"\n✅ Accuracy: {accuracy_score(df_val['labels'], pred_labels):.4f}")
    print("\n📊 Classification Report:")
    print(classification_report(df_val['labels'], pred_labels, target_names=le.classes_))

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()

In [ ]:
df_pred = pd.read_csv("kobert_val_predictions.csv", encoding="utf-8")

y_true = df_pred["true_label"].values
y_pred = df_pred["pred_label"].values

labels = sorted(list(set(y_true) | set(y_pred)))

# 혼동 행렬 계산
cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred, labels=labels)

# 혼동 행렬 시각화
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt="d", cmap="Blues", xticklabels=labels, yticklabels=labels)
plt.xlabel("Predicted Label")
plt.ylabel("True Label")
plt.title("Confusion Matrix")
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.yticks(rotation=0)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

  • Weighted F1-score: 0.94
  • Achieved F1-scores above 0.85 in nearly all categories,
    with particularly strong performance (F1 > 0.97) in high-volume classes such as Automobile, Transportation, and Safety & Construction.

📊 Per-Class Performance Analysis¶

  • F1-score ≥ 0.90: Automobile, Transportation, Taxation, Environmental Cleaning, Water & Sewage
  • Minority classes also performed well:
    • Information & Communication: F1 = 0.92
    • Land: F1 = 0.87
  • Excellent balance between recall and precision, indicating no significant data bias.

🧾 Confusion Matrix Interpretation¶

  • Most predictions fall accurately along the diagonal, indicating strong class distinction
  • Very few misclassifications, mostly between similar categories (e.g., General, Administration)

📌 Overall Evaluation¶

Metric Result
Accuracy 0.9384
Macro F1 0.92
Model Size Base
Encoding Method Tokens + Attention Mask (token_type_ids = 0)
Usability ✅ Suitable for real-world service deployment

🤖 Classification Performance using KLUE RoBERTa¶

✅ Model Details¶

  • Model: klue/roberta-base
  • Max Input Length: 128
  • Token Type IDs: Not used (RoBERTa architecture does not require them)
  • Training Method: Hugging Face Trainer with EarlyStopping
  • Data Encoding:
    • Labels stored under the labels column
    • Tokenizer uses truncation for input sequences
In [ ]:
import os
os.environ["CUDA_LAUNCH_BLOCKING"] = "1"

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import torch
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report
from datasets import Dataset
from transformers import (
    AutoTokenizer,
    AutoModelForSequenceClassification,
    Trainer,
    TrainingArguments,
    DataCollatorWithPadding,
    EarlyStoppingCallback
)

# 데이터 로딩 및 인코딩 (컬럼명: labels)
def load_and_encode_data(train_path, val_path):
    df_train = pd.read_csv(train_path)
    df_val = pd.read_csv(val_path)

    le = LabelEncoder()
    df_train['labels'] = le.fit_transform(df_train['category'])
    df_val['labels'] = le.transform(df_val['category'])

    return df_train, df_val, le

# 토크나이징 함수
def tokenize_dataset(dataset, tokenizer):
    def tokenize_fn(batch):
        return tokenizer(batch['text'], truncation=True, max_length=128)
    return dataset.map(tokenize_fn, batched=True)

# 평가 함수
def compute_metrics(eval_pred):
    logits, labels = eval_pred
    preds = np.argmax(logits, axis=-1)
    return {"accuracy": accuracy_score(labels, preds)}

# 메인 실행
def main():
    model_name = "klue/roberta-base"
    train_path = "민원통합데이터.csv"
    val_path = "민원통합데이터.csv"

    # 데이터 로딩 및 인코딩
    df_train, df_val, le = load_and_encode_data(train_path, val_path)

    # HuggingFace Dataset 생성
    dataset_train = Dataset.from_pandas(df_train[["text", "labels"]])
    dataset_val = Dataset.from_pandas(df_val[["text", "labels"]])

    # 토크나이저 및 토큰화
    tokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained(model_name, use_fast=True)
    tokenized_train = tokenize_dataset(dataset_train, tokenizer)
    tokenized_val = tokenize_dataset(dataset_val, tokenizer)

    # 동적 패딩용 Collator
    data_collator = DataCollatorWithPadding(tokenizer=tokenizer)

    # 모델 로딩
    model = AutoModelForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained(model_name, num_labels=len(le.classes_))

    # 훈련 인자
    training_args = TrainingArguments(
        output_dir="./roberta-results",
        eval_strategy="epoch",
        save_strategy="epoch",
        learning_rate=2e-5,
        per_device_train_batch_size=64,
        per_device_eval_batch_size=64,
        num_train_epochs=100,
        weight_decay=0.01,
        load_best_model_at_end=True,
        metric_for_best_model="eval_loss",
        greater_is_better=False,
        logging_dir="./roberta-logs",
        fp16=torch.cuda.is_available(),
        dataloader_num_workers=4
    )

    # Trainer 생성
    trainer = Trainer(
        model=model,
        args=training_args,
        train_dataset=tokenized_train,
        eval_dataset=tokenized_val,
        tokenizer=tokenizer,
        compute_metrics=compute_metrics,
        data_collator=data_collator,
        callbacks=[EarlyStoppingCallback(early_stopping_patience=10)]
    )

    # 학습 시작
    trainer.train()

    # 모델 저장
    model.save_pretrained("./roberta_final_model")
    tokenizer.save_pretrained("./roberta_final_model")

    # 검증 예측 및 저장
    preds_output = trainer.predict(tokenized_val)
    pred_labels = np.argmax(preds_output.predictions, axis=-1)

    result_df = pd.DataFrame({
        "text": df_val["text"],
        "true_label": df_val["category"],
        "pred_label": le.inverse_transform(pred_labels)
    })
    result_df.to_csv("roberta_val_predictions.csv", index=False, encoding="utf-8")

    # 평가 출력
    print(f"\n✅ Accuracy: {accuracy_score(df_val['labels'], pred_labels):.4f}")
    print("\n📊 Classification Report:")
    print(classification_report(df_val['labels'], pred_labels, target_names=le.classes_))

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()

df_pred = pd.read_csv("roberta_val_predictions.csv", encoding="utf-8")

y_true = df_pred["true_label"].values
y_pred = df_pred["pred_label"].values

labels = sorted(list(set(y_true) | set(y_pred)))

cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred, labels=labels)

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt="d", cmap="Blues", xticklabels=labels, yticklabels=labels)
plt.xlabel("Predicted Label")
plt.ylabel("True Label")
plt.title("Confusion Matrix")
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.yticks(rotation=0)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

🎯 Performance Summary¶

  • Accuracy: 0.9393
  • Macro F1-score: 0.92
  • Weighted F1-score: 0.94
  • Demonstrated consistently strong performance across all classes,
    including well-balanced classification results for minority categories.

📊 Per-Class Performance Analysis¶

  • F1-score ≥ 0.90: Automobile, Transportation, Environmental Cleaning, Water & Sewage,
    Taxation, Public Health Center, Welfare, Culture/Sports/Tourism

  • Minority classes also stable:

    • Information & Communication: F1 = 0.90
    • Land, Administration: F1 = 0.86, 0.84

  • Slight drop in recall for General category (81%)
    → likely due to semantic overlap with multiple classes

🧾 Confusion Matrix Interpretation¶

  • High density along the diagonal → accurate classification overall
  • Minor class confusion observed between similar categories (e.g., General, Administration)
  • Very few misclassifications among high-frequency classes → indicates stable model performance

📌 Overall Evaluation¶

Metric Result
Accuracy 0.9393
Macro F1 0.92
Model Size Base
Encoding Method RoBERTa structure (no token_type_ids)

⚡️ Classification Performance using KcELECTRA (beomi)¶

✅ Model Details¶

  • Model: beomi/KcELECTRA-base
  • Max Input Length: 128
  • Token Type IDs: Not used (ELECTRA architecture does not require them)
  • Training Method: Hugging Face Trainer with EarlyStopping
  • Data Processing:
    • Labels stored in the labels column
    • Tokenizer applied with truncation only
In [ ]:
import os
os.environ["CUDA_LAUNCH_BLOCKING"] = "1"

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import torch
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report
from datasets import Dataset
from transformers import (
    AutoTokenizer,
    AutoModelForSequenceClassification,
    Trainer,
    TrainingArguments,
    DataCollatorWithPadding,
    EarlyStoppingCallback
)

# 데이터 로딩 및 라벨 인코딩
def load_and_encode_data(train_path, val_path):
    df_train = pd.read_csv(train_path)
    df_val = pd.read_csv(val_path)

    le = LabelEncoder()
    df_train['labels'] = le.fit_transform(df_train['category'])
    df_val['labels'] = le.transform(df_val['category'])

    return df_train, df_val, le

# 토크나이징 함수
def tokenize_dataset(dataset, tokenizer):
    def tokenize_fn(batch):
        return tokenizer(batch['text'], truncation=True, max_length=128)
    return dataset.map(tokenize_fn, batched=True)

# 평가 메트릭
def compute_metrics(eval_pred):
    logits, labels = eval_pred
    preds = np.argmax(logits, axis=-1)
    return {"accuracy": accuracy_score(labels, preds)}

# 메인 실행
def main():
    model_name = "beomi/KcELECTRA-base"
    train_path = "민원통합데이터_train.csv"
    val_path = "민원통합데이터_val.csv"

    # 데이터 로딩 및 변환
    df_train, df_val, le = load_and_encode_data(train_path, val_path)
    dataset_train = Dataset.from_pandas(df_train[['text', 'labels']])
    dataset_val = Dataset.from_pandas(df_val[['text', 'labels']])

    # 토크나이저 및 토큰화
    tokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained(model_name, use_fast=True)
    tokenized_train = tokenize_dataset(dataset_train, tokenizer)
    tokenized_val = tokenize_dataset(dataset_val, tokenizer)

    data_collator = DataCollatorWithPadding(tokenizer=tokenizer)

    # 모델 로딩
    model = AutoModelForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained(model_name, num_labels=len(le.classes_))

    # 학습 설정
    training_args = TrainingArguments(
        output_dir="./kcelectra-results",
        eval_strategy="epoch",
        save_strategy="epoch",
        learning_rate=2e-5,
        per_device_train_batch_size=64,
        per_device_eval_batch_size=64,
        num_train_epochs=100,
        weight_decay=0.01,
        load_best_model_at_end=True,
        metric_for_best_model="eval_loss",
        greater_is_better=False,
        logging_dir="./kcelectra-logs",
        fp16=torch.cuda.is_available(),
        dataloader_num_workers=4
    )

    # Trainer 생성
    trainer = Trainer(
        model=model,
        args=training_args,
        train_dataset=tokenized_train,
        eval_dataset=tokenized_val,
        tokenizer=tokenizer,
        compute_metrics=compute_metrics,
        data_collator=data_collator,
        callbacks=[EarlyStoppingCallback(early_stopping_patience=10)]
    )

    # 학습
    trainer.train()

    # 모델 저장
    model.save_pretrained("./kcelectra_final_model")
    tokenizer.save_pretrained("./kcelectra_final_model")

    # 예측
    preds_output = trainer.predict(tokenized_val)
    pred_labels = np.argmax(preds_output.predictions, axis=-1)

    result_df = pd.DataFrame({
        "text": df_val["text"],
        "true_label": df_val["category"],
        "pred_label": le.inverse_transform(pred_labels)
    })
    result_df.to_csv("kcelectra_val_predictions.csv", index=False, encoding="utf-8")

    # 평가 출력
    print(f"\n✅ Accuracy: {accuracy_score(df_val['labels'], pred_labels):.4f}")
    print("\n📊 Classification Report:")
    print(classification_report(df_val['labels'], pred_labels, target_names=le.classes_))

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()

In [ ]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix

df_pred = pd.read_csv("kcelectra_val_predictions.csv", encoding="utf-8")

y_true = df_pred["true_label"].values
y_pred = df_pred["pred_label"].values

labels = sorted(list(set(y_true) | set(y_pred)))

cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred, labels=labels)

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt="d", cmap="Blues", xticklabels=labels, yticklabels=labels)
plt.xlabel("Predicted Label")
plt.ylabel("True Label")
plt.title("Confusion Matrix")
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.yticks(rotation=0)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

🎯 Performance Summary¶

  • Accuracy: 0.9332
  • Macro F1-score: 0.91
  • Weighted F1-score: 0.93
  • Overall, the model demonstrated very high performance
    with strong robustness against class imbalance.

📊 Per-Class Performance Analysis¶

  • F1-score ≥ 0.90:
    Automobile, Transportation, Water & Sewage, Taxation,
    Public Health Center, Welfare, Sanitation, Safety & Construction

  • Minority classes also performed well:

    • Information & Communication: F1 = 0.89
    • Land: F1 = 0.85
    • Administration: F1 = 0.83

  • Some classes showed slightly lower performance
    (e.g., General, Culture/Sports/Tourism, Forestry) with F1 around 0.80–0.85

🧾 Confusion Matrix Interpretation¶

  • Most predictions aligned accurately along the diagonal
  • Minor misclassifications between similar classes (e.g., General ↔ Transportation, Administration ↔ Welfare)
  • Minority classes were also classified reliably, indicating good real-world applicability

📌 Overall Evaluation¶

Metric Result
Accuracy 0.9332
Macro F1 0.91
Model Size Base
Encoding Method Truncation only

✅ Final Conclusion¶

🛠 Data Preprocessing Summary¶

  • Merged source data (text) and labeled data (category) using an inner join on id to ensure data integrity
  • Removed duplicate entries based on text, keeping only the most frequent category per group
  • After preprocessing, the dataset showed a severe imbalance (Train 97% / Validation 2.7%)
    → 10% of the training data was stratified and moved to the validation set to balance the split

📊 Model Performance Comparison¶

  • Multiple models were evaluated and compared
  • Among them, SKT's KoBERT model (skt/kobert-base-v1) achieved the best performance
Model Accuracy Macro F1 Weighted F1 Notes
LightGBM 0.6151 0.50 0.60 Baseline
KoBERT (SKT) ✅ 0.9384 0.92 0.94 ✅ Final selected model
RoBERTa (KLUE) 0.9393 0.92 0.94
KcELECTRA (beomi) 0.9332 0.91 0.93

🏆 Final Model: SKT KoBERT¶

  • Delivered the most stable and powerful performance in terms of overall accuracy and class balance
  • Achieved high prediction reliability even for minority classes (e.g., Information & Communication, Land) with F1 > 0.85
  • Final classification accuracy: 93.8%

🧩 Deployment & Application¶

  • The trained KoBERT model has been deployed on Hugging Face Spaces
    where users can input complaint text and receive real-time category predictions

  • Based on the predicted category, the system provides the official website and contact number
    of the corresponding central government department responsible for handling the complaint
